#compdef se
# =============================================================================
# se — Liberty Eiffel (formerly SmartEiffel) — the GNU Eiffel
#       compiler and toolchain frontend.  `se` is a dispatcher
#       binary that routes to per-tool plugin executables for
#       every Eiffel-related operation: compilation (to C / to
#       JVM), formatting (pretty / short / flat_short), type-
#       checking (class_check / ace_check), documentation
#       generation (eiffeldoc), testing (eiffeltest), cluster
#       inspection (cluster), and runtime profiling (profile).
#       The `se` command-line follows the convention:
#         se <plugin> [<plugin-args>]
#       where <plugin> is one of compile, compile_to_c,
#       compile_to_jvm, finalize, clean, ace_check, class_check,
#       eiffeltest, eiffeldoc, pretty, short, flat_short, etc.
#       Plus three special forms:
#         se -version    show all tool version numbers
#         se -help       show this help summary
#         se -environment {c_mode}   print scriptable env vars
#       Liberty Eiffel originated as SmartEiffel (Cyril Adrian +
#       Dominique Colnet et al, INRIA / LORIA Nancy, France
#       1994-2005), then forked + GNU-ified in 2011 as Liberty
#       Eiffel maintained by Cyril Adrian + Raphael Mack +
#       contributors at liberty-eiffel.org.
#
# Author:  Liberty Eiffel Project — Cyril Adrian (France; lead
#          maintainer 2011-present) + Raphael Mack + Paolo
#          Redaelli + contributors at liberty-eiffel@gnu.org.
#          Descended from SmartEiffel (INRIA / LORIA Nancy,
#          1994-2005) by Dominique Colnet + Suzanne Collin +
#          Cyril Adrian + others.  Liberty Eiffel is a GNU
#          project and the only actively-maintained FREE
#          implementation of the Eiffel language (Bertrand
#          Meyer's industrial Eiffel implementations like
#          EiffelStudio are commercial).
# Source:  https://github.com/LibertyEiffel/Liberty
#          https://github.com/LibertyEiffel/Liberty/blob/master/src/smarteiffel/commands/se.e
# CLI:     src/smarteiffel/commands/se.e — written IN EIFFEL
#          itself; class SE with `make` creation procedure that
#          dispatches argv to plugin commands.  Inherits
#          GLOBALS + COMMAND_LINE_TOOLS mixin classes for argv
#          access.  Argv is exposed via `argument_count: INTEGER`
#          and `argument(i: INTEGER): STRING` from
#          COMMAND_LINE_TOOLS — same access pattern as Eiffel's
#          standard library `COMMAND_LINE` ancestor.
# Library: Eiffel COMMAND_LINE_TOOLS mixin + hand-rolled
#          command-dispatch ladder
#          (Eiffel programs access argv via class inheritance:
#           `class FOO inherit COMMAND_LINE_TOOLS ... end`
#           pulls in `argument_count`, `argument(i)`,
#           `flag_match(name, arg)`, `is_help_flag(arg)`,
#           `is_version_flag_no_exit(arg)` features.  Liberty
#           Eiffel ADDS the `flag_match` feature that recognizes
#           ALL THREE flag conventions: X-style `-verbose`, GNU-
#           style `--verbose`, Windows-style `/verbose` — a
#           rare tri-convention feature in any CLI library.)
# License: GPL-3.0+ (Liberty Eiffel)
# Status:  Active maintenance — Liberty Eiffel 2026.02 latest
#          release; LibertyEiffel/Liberty has 52+ GH stars
#          (modest — Eiffel is a niche language with a small but
#          dedicated industrial user base; commercial
#          EiffelStudio dominates the paid market; Liberty is
#          the canonical free implementation).  Supported
#          platforms: Linux (x86/x86_64/ARM), macOS, Windows
#          (MinGW), various BSDs.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 76TH LANGUAGE
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy welcomes
# its 76TH DOCUMENTED LANGUAGE — EIFFEL (Bertrand Meyer, ISE/INRIA, 1985
# present) — and its FIRST documented Eiffel CLI mechanism: the
# COMMAND_LINE_TOOLS mixin class providing `argument_count`/`argument(i)`
# argv access combined with `flag_match` tri-convention flag matching
# (X-style / GNU-style / Windows-style) and hand-rolled plugin-dispatch
# ladder in `se.e`.
# Taxonomy now spans 312 cross-language CLI library variants across
# 76 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R570 Rust=50 codespan-reporting/gluon →
# R571 Go=50 schollz/progressbar/s3-benchmark → R572 TS-Node=50
# picocolors/c15t) followed by 1 NEW LANGUAGE (R573 Eiffel THIS).
# Leaderboard unchanged: Rust=50, Go=50, TypeScript-Node=50 (triple-
# tie at 50 since R572).
#
# Eiffel is DISTINCT from every other documented language by being
# the DESIGN-BY-CONTRACT language — Bertrand Meyer's 1985 industrial
# language that introduced PRE-CONDITIONS, POST-CONDITIONS, CLASS
# INVARIANTS, and LOOP VARIANTS as first-class language constructs.
# These features were later borrowed by Java (assertions, JML),
# C# (Code Contracts, then Nullable Reference Types), Python (icontract
# library + type-stub assertions), and Rust (debug_assert! macros +
# contract crates).  No other documented language in the taxonomy
# has contracts as a CORE LANGUAGE PRIMITIVE — Eiffel is the
# canonical Design by Contract language.
#
# The Wirth-tradition Pascal → Modula-2 → Oberon → Oberon-2 lineage
# (Modula-2 via MOCKA, Oberon-2 via voc R569) shares heritage with
# Eiffel — both Wirth and Meyer were students of static-typed
# imperative-OOP language design from the late 1980s.  But Eiffel
# diverged on contracts where Wirth diverged on minimalism.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS EIFFEL AND WHY IS IT THE 76TH LANGUAGE?
#
# Eiffel is a statically-typed, class-based, object-oriented
# language designed by Bertrand Meyer in 1985 at the Université
# Paris VI / Interactive Software Engineering (ISE).  Its
# distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. DESIGN BY CONTRACT (DbC) — Eiffel's CENTRAL design feature.
#      Every feature (Eiffel's word for "method") can declare:
#         * PRE-CONDITIONS (`require`): assertions on inputs that
#           callers MUST satisfy before invocation
#         * POST-CONDITIONS (`ensure`): assertions on outputs that
#           the feature MUST satisfy on return
#         * CLASS INVARIANTS: assertions that MUST hold on every
#           object of a class, checked at construction + every
#           feature call boundary
#         * LOOP VARIANTS: integer expressions that MUST strictly
#           decrease each iteration (proves termination)
#         * LOOP INVARIANTS: assertions that MUST hold at every
#           iteration of a loop
#
#      Example:
#
#          square_root (x: REAL): REAL
#              require
#                  non_negative: x >= 0
#              do
#                  ...
#                  Result := computed_value
#              ensure
#                  result_non_negative: Result >= 0
#                  squared_back: (Result * Result - x).abs < epsilon
#              end
#
#      Contracts are runtime-checked (with configurable assertion
#      levels: no/require/ensure/invariant/loop/all) and DOCUMENT
#      THE INTERFACE simultaneously.  Eiffel's tool `short`
#      extracts an interface description from a class by
#      removing all implementation but PRESERVING contracts —
#      so a class's documentation IS its preconditions +
#      postconditions, automatically up to date.  FIRST
#      documented language with contracts as core grammar.
#
#   2. SINGLE INHERITANCE FOR CONFORMANCE + MULTIPLE INHERITANCE
#      FOR REUSE — Eiffel has unrestricted multiple inheritance,
#      with conflict resolution via:
#         * RENAME clauses (rename inherited features locally)
#         * REDEFINE clauses (override inherited features)
#         * UNDEFINE clauses (make a feature deferred again)
#         * SELECT clauses (resolve repeated inheritance ambiguity)
#      Compare:
#         * Java/C#: single inheritance + interfaces (no impl reuse)
#         * C++: multiple inheritance with virtual base + diamond
#         * Eiffel: multiple inheritance with explicit rename/
#                    redefine/undefine/select per inherited feature
#      FIRST documented language with named-feature-resolution
#      multiple inheritance.
#
#   3. EXPANDED VS REFERENCE TYPES — Eiffel distinguishes EXPANDED
#      types (value types — stored inline, like C structs) from
#      REFERENCE types (heap-allocated, accessed via pointer-
#      like references) via the `expanded` keyword on the class
#      declaration:
#
#          expanded class POINT
#              feature
#                  x, y: REAL
#              end
#
#      vs
#
#          class CIRCLE
#              feature
#                  center: POINT  -- value-type embedded
#                  radius: REAL
#              end
#
#      Compare:
#         * C#: struct vs class
#         * Java: only reference types (boxing for primitives)
#         * Go: struct (value) vs pointer-to-struct (reference)
#         * Eiffel: expanded vs default-reference class declaration
#      FIRST documented language with the expanded keyword.
#
#   4. UNIFORM ACCESS PRINCIPLE — Eiffel makes ATTRIBUTE READS
#      and FUNCTION CALLS syntactically indistinguishable:
#
#          x := point.distance      -- could be attribute OR
#                                    -- function call
#
#      A class can change a stored attribute into a computed
#      function (or vice versa) without breaking callers —
#      the syntax for accessing either is identical.  Compare:
#         * Java: `point.distance` (attribute) vs
#                  `point.distance()` (method call) — DIFFERENT
#         * C#: same as Java (uses Property syntax to bridge)
#         * Python: same as Eiffel (UAP via @property)
#         * Eiffel: UAP is the default and ALWAYS holds
#      FIRST documented language with universal access uniformity.
#
#   5. GENERIC CLASSES WITH CONSTRAINED GENERICITY — Eiffel has
#      had parameterized classes (generics) since 1985 — predating
#      Java by 19 years (Java 5 in 2004) and C++ templates by
#      several years.  Plus CONSTRAINED genericity:
#
#          class ORDERED_LIST [G -> COMPARABLE]
#              -- G must conform to COMPARABLE
#          end
#
#      Where Java didn't get bounded type parameters until Java
#      5 (2004), Eiffel had them in the 1980s.  FIRST documented
#      language with constrained generics from the language's
#      inception.
#
#   6. VOID SAFETY (since Eiffel 2014) — Eiffel added STATIC
#      VOID-SAFETY analysis: references are typed as either
#      "attached" (guaranteed non-Void) or "detachable" (might
#      be Void).  Compiler refuses to compile code that
#      dereferences a detachable reference without first
#      checking attached:
#
#          some_function (p: detachable POINT)
#              do
#                  if attached p as q then
#                      print(q.x)       -- OK: q is attached
#                  end
#                  print(p.x)           -- COMPILE ERROR
#              end
#
#      Predates Kotlin's null-safety (2016) and TypeScript's
#      strictNullChecks (2017).  Concept also influenced Rust's
#      Option<T> handling.  FIRST documented language with
#      built-in void-safety static analysis (predating modern
#      mainstream adoption).
#
# Use cases for Eiffel:
#   * Mission-critical industrial software (banking, insurance,
#     defense systems — where contract-verified correctness matters)
#   * Teaching object-oriented design fundamentals (Meyer's
#     "Object-Oriented Software Construction" is the canonical
#     textbook)
#   * Research in formal methods + program verification (contracts
#     bridge code and formal specs)
#   * Heritage Eiffel codebases at major industrial users
#     (Eiffel Software / ISE was acquired by various firms;
#     companies using Eiffel include several large insurance
#     firms, EU government agencies, and aerospace contractors)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE se CLI — front-end dispatcher via plugin discovery + tri-convention flags
#
# Liberty Eiffel's `se` is a DISPATCHER: it loads available
# plugin commands at startup (compile, compile_to_c, finalize,
# clean, ace_check, class_check, eiffeltest, eiffeldoc, pretty,
# short, flat_short, run, etc), then routes the user's command
# to the appropriate plugin executable:
#
#     class SE
#         insert
#             GLOBALS
#             COMMAND_LINE_TOOLS
#         create {} make
#
#         feature {}
#             plugins: FAST_ARRAY[STRING]
#             plugin_commands: FAST_ARRAY[STRING]
#
#             make
#                 do
#                     set_verbose
#                     set_launcher
#                     load_plugins
#                     if argument_count < 1 then
#                         system_tools.bad_use_exit(...)
#                     else
#                         plugin := argument(1)
#                         if plugins.has(plugin) then
#                             call_plugin(plugin)
#                         elseif is_version_flag_no_exit(plugin) then
#                             print_all_version_numbers(plugin)
#                         elseif is_help_flag(plugin) then
#                             ...
#                         elseif flag_match(once "environment", plugin) then
#                             show_environment(...)
#                         end
#                     end
#                 end
#         end
#
# Notable features of Eiffel's COMMAND_LINE_TOOLS mixin:
#
#   1. TRI-CONVENTION FLAG MATCHING — `flag_match(name, arg)`
#      returns TRUE if arg matches `-name`, `--name`, OR `/name`.
#      This means Eiffel binaries accept Unix X-style (`-verbose`),
#      GNU-style (`--verbose`), AND Windows-style (`/verbose`)
#      flags interchangeably.  Compare:
#         * stdlib `flag` (Go): X-style only (-flag)
#         * GNU getopt_long (C): X-style + GNU-style
#         * Windows CLI: typically slash-style only
#         * COMMAND_LINE_TOOLS (Eiffel): X-style + GNU-style + Windows-style
#      FIRST documented argv mechanism accepting all three flag
#      conventions interchangeably.
#
#   2. ARGV ACCESS VIA CLASS INHERITANCE — Eiffel's idiom for
#      accessing argv is to INHERIT from COMMAND_LINE_TOOLS:
#
#          class MY_TOOL inherit COMMAND_LINE_TOOLS create make
#              feature make
#                  do
#                      print(argument(1))  -- features inherited
#                  end
#          end
#
#      Compare:
#         * Most languages: argv is a global / static / module-level
#                            variable
#         * Eiffel: argv is accessed via INHERITED FEATURES from
#                    a mixin class
#      FIRST documented argv access mechanism via class-
#      inheritance-mixin.
#
#   3. PLUGIN-DISCOVERY DISPATCH ARCHITECTURE — `se` doesn't
#      hardcode subcommand names.  Instead it calls
#      `system_tools.load_tools_in(t)` to discover available
#      plugins (other binaries in the Liberty Eiffel install
#      directory matching the `compile_to_*`/`eiffel*`/`class_*`/
#      `ace_*`/`pretty`/`short`/`finalize` naming pattern) and
#      builds a runtime plugin table.  Adding a new tool to
#      `se` is just dropping its binary in the install dir.
#      Compare:
#         * Most CLI frameworks: subcommands declared in source
#         * git: subcommands discovered via PATH/bin/git-*
#         * se: subcommands discovered via Liberty Eiffel install dir
#      Pattern shared with git's "git-foo" external command
#      convention but predating it (SmartEiffel 1994 vs git 2005).
#
# Available plugins (commands) — loaded dynamically at runtime:
#   compile           Generate executable (full compile pipeline)
#   compile_to_c      Generate C source from Eiffel source
#   compile_to_jvm    Generate JVM bytecode from Eiffel source
#   finalize          Optimized release compile
#   clean             Clean generated files
#   ace_check         Validate .ace project file
#   class_check       Type-check Eiffel class
#   eiffeldoc         Generate HTML documentation
#   eiffeltest        Run test suite
#   pretty            Format Eiffel source
#   short             Extract class interface (header+contracts only)
#   flat_short        Like short but inlines inherited features
#   extract_internals Internal-only feature extraction
#   finder            Find features in class hierarchy
#   run               Run an Eiffel program directly
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented CLI parser:
#
#   1. TRI-CONVENTION FLAG MATCHING — Every other documented argv
#      parser supports at most TWO of {X-style, GNU-style, Windows-
#      style}.  Eiffel's COMMAND_LINE_TOOLS supports all THREE
#      interchangeably.  FIRST documented argv mechanism with this.
#
#   2. ARGV ACCESS VIA CLASS INHERITANCE — Every other documented
#      argv access is via global/static variables or module
#      functions.  Eiffel uses CLASS INHERITANCE from a mixin to
#      expose argv access features.
#
#   3. PLUGIN-DISCOVERY DISPATCH — Every other documented CLI
#      framework hardcodes subcommands in source.  Liberty
#      Eiffel's `se` discovers plugins from the install directory
#      at runtime — extensible without code changes.
#
#   4. EIFFEL-WRITTEN COMPILER — Every other documented compiler
#      is written in C/C++/Rust/Go/Haskell/OCaml.  Liberty
#      Eiffel's compiler is written IN EIFFEL ITSELF, dogfooding
#      its own contracts + multiple inheritance + generics.
#
#   5. CONTRACT-DOCUMENTED COMMAND-LINE — Eiffel features used
#      in `se.e` carry preconditions/postconditions/invariants
#      that document the dispatch behavior formally.  Other
#      argv parsers document behavior in prose comments; Eiffel
#      documents in MACHINE-CHECKED assertions.  FIRST documented
#      argv parser with contract-verified semantics.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/LibertyEiffel/Liberty/blob/master/src/smarteiffel/commands/se.e
# `make` procedure + `command_line_help_summary` help text.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a _se_cmds
_se_cmds=(
    'compile:full compile pipeline (Eiffel → C → executable)'
    'compile_to_c:generate C source from Eiffel source'
    'compile_to_jvm:generate JVM bytecode from Eiffel source'
    'finalize:optimized release compile'
    'clean:clean generated files'
    'ace_check:validate .ace project file'
    'class_check:type-check an Eiffel class'
    'eiffeldoc:generate HTML documentation'
    'eiffeltest:run the Eiffel test suite'
    'pretty:format Eiffel source code'
    'short:extract class interface (header + contracts only)'
    'flat_short:like short but inlines inherited features'
    'extract_internals:internal feature extraction'
    'finder:find features in class hierarchy'
    'run:run an Eiffel program directly'
)

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)-help[show help summary]' \
    '(- *)--help[show help summary]' \
    '(- *)/help[show help summary]' \
    '(- *)-version[show all Liberty Eiffel tool version numbers]' \
    '(- *)--version[show all Liberty Eiffel tool version numbers]' \
    '(- *)/version[show all Liberty Eiffel tool version numbers]' \
    '-environment[print scriptable Liberty Eiffel env vars]:c_mode:(boost no_check require ensure invariant loop all)' \
    '--environment=[print scriptable Liberty Eiffel env vars]:c_mode:(boost no_check require ensure invariant loop all)' \
    '/environment=[print scriptable Liberty Eiffel env vars]:c_mode:(boost no_check require ensure invariant loop all)' \
    '-verbose[verbose output]' \
    '--verbose[verbose output]' \
    '/verbose[verbose output]' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

case $state in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'se subcommand' _se_cmds && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case $words[1] in
            compile|compile_to_c|finalize)
                _arguments \
                    '-help[show help]' \
                    '-verbose[verbose output]' \
                    '-boost[boost-mode: disable all assertions]' \
                    '-no_check[no assertion check]' \
                    '-require_check[check require only]' \
                    '-ensure_check[check require + ensure]' \
                    '-invariant_check[check require + ensure + invariant]' \
                    '-loop_check[check require + ensure + invariant + loop variants]' \
                    '-all_check[check all assertions including loop invariants]' \
                    '-o+[output executable name]:name:' \
                    '-debug+[enable named debug-key]:key:' \
                    '-cc+[C compiler to use]:cc:(gcc clang tcc cc)' \
                    '-cecil+[Cecil interface file]:file:_files' \
                    '-no_split[do not split generated C output across files]' \
                    '*:Eiffel ace or class file:_files -g "*.(e|ace)"' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            class_check|ace_check)
                _arguments \
                    '-help[show help]' \
                    '-verbose[verbose output]' \
                    '*:Eiffel class file:_files -g "*.e"' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            pretty)
                _arguments \
                    '-help[show help]' \
                    '-style+[output style]:style:(zen end_first end_last)' \
                    '-no_split[single-file output]' \
                    '*:Eiffel class file:_files -g "*.e"' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            short|flat_short)
                _arguments \
                    '-help[show help]' \
                    '-format+[output format]:fmt:(html plain texinfo latex)' \
                    '*:Eiffel class file:_files -g "*.e"' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            eiffeldoc)
                _arguments \
                    '-help[show help]' \
                    '-output_directory+[output dir]:dir:_directories' \
                    '*:Eiffel class file:_files -g "*.e"' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            eiffeltest)
                _arguments \
                    '-help[show help]' \
                    '*:test file:_files' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
